In article <1992Mar31.195025.18689@qualcomm.com> karn@chicago.qualcomm.com (Phil Karn) writes:
>There is one possible countermeasure that the FBI could use against
>such phones -- just get the local phone company to introduce enough
>noise or timing jitter to force the "suspect" to go clear instead of
>using his secure phone.

Given that noise and timing jitter would also affect FAX and
other transmissions, I doubt that the telco could get away
with this for long.  And ISDN would either be immune or
taken down completely by such a tactic.

It does look like very good privacy will soon be available,
regardless of how little our government likes it.
